72
00:03:57.665 --> 00:04:02.625
It is made of two layers, like this, you see, an inner layer, an outer layer.

73
00:04:02.885 --> 00:04:06.425
And this is where you understand what is called a retinal detachment.

74
00:04:06.985 --> 00:04:08.545
We can clearly see these two layers.

75
00:04:10.025 --> 00:04:12.565
Well, when people have a retinal detachment,

76
00:04:12.636 --> 00:04:17.776
it is this layer that expands, it is this space between the inner leaflet

77
00:04:17.776 --> 00:04:19.476
and the outer leaflet of the retina.

78
00:04:20.156 --> 00:04:25.196
There will be another very thin layer here, which will be very important later, it is

79
00:04:25.196 --> 00:04:27.636
what is called the pigmentary layer.

80
00:04:28.716 --> 00:04:33.996
You will discuss this, I think, in detail tomorrow, it is the entire layer of this retina with

81
00:04:33.996 --> 00:04:36.436
the pigmentary layer,

82
00:04:36.596 --> 00:04:40.636
and then what are called the photoreceptors, which are of the type that you...

83
00:04:40.707 --> 00:04:46.047
know as cones and rods. But you also have a layer called

84
00:04:46.047 --> 00:04:52.187
the ganglion cells. It is truly an important layer for

85
00:04:52.187 --> 00:04:53.507
